A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama's Re-Election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It was in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws starting in 2009 that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum following the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 States were introduced during the year 2011 alone.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the periods of early voting, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the election and withdraw citizens with a judicial record their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
However, it often costs more than one hundred dollars to obtain the required ID card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
A lot more.
Students, voters considered to be voting more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their identity card with photo issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
Two out of three Hispanic voters are in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers sponsored laws in 2011 that abolished voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million citizens.
However, measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter represented only 13% of the state’s voters.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
These only represented 11% of the electorate, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites who made up 76% of voters represented only 46% of voters voting in advance.
Of course, the Democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several bills have been blocked by vetoes from Democratic governors.
The Attorney General of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on and see it as an obvious goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Centre shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
