The Higgs boson debarked
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, just that.
And then it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "lesser" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that this is Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but data is still lacking to be perfectly sure.
Let's assume it's Higgs anyway, since the chances of getting it wrong seem slim, and let's see what it's about.
There is, in this low world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In a corner, we find good citizens called Fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for that principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not approach here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be in some way related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all beasts as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in this specific place, a bit like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "interference" arises an electromagnetic wave (of light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disrupted" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, a little as if it were a frozen pond of which only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why we need a huge particle accelerator like CERN's - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is not all particles, or all materials, that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while others (like the photon, yours) do not.
Now, what “can bring” all this research, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any gaps between MS observations and predictions.
Moreover, there are many to be wished that we could find them, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physical" and clog some holes in the Model.
This, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, proposing no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oops!).
But no such deviations have been found at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of this research in the daily life of Mr and Mrs All-the-World are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will not be any.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, the pioneers of the laser, in the Bell Laboratories, did not suspect the revolution that their work was going to trigger.
They were looking at scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed), in 1962 - already told us that the laser was initially seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work on optics.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original intention, now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this doesn’t mean that the LHC’s activities will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, we never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die...
With its Commission to Die in Dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is expected to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
