The prostate cancer that bit him had left him a two-year pause.
"They had given me five years to live, I was seven years old," he said, half fig half grape, lying in his bed at the palliative care home Victor-Gadbois, of Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its job: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even from eating alone.
Stuck in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even smiles, speaks to strangers who fight around him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this ailment.
"During our lives, we learn that a man pisses standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Regressing to the child’s stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to accept regression, he notes.
Because, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments are unfolding at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “consciously and stifled.”
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
"I don't have any wishes in life anymore," she said, before accepting that she's being put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the coming days, however, she awaits a final visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, we provide, with a group of volunteers, body care and food assistance.
These are palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when we know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
As a dying person, we will agree to provide oral care to brandy or Pepsi, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we had a beer for Mr. X, who passed away last night.
This morning, it is his son who will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as much as patients,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the house of Victor-Gadbois, the days follow but do not resemble each other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man enjoying his last family gathering in the yard, tucked in his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
“For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal phase of his or her life, whether at home, in the hospital or in the nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Société de cares palliatives <0xC3><0xA0> domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this great shortage in Quebec's health care that makes several physicians specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care summits including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before they agree to euthanasia.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without being done what is necessary to relieve her.
I'm afraid patients only ask to die because they don't get proper care.
And at the same time, several oncologists have been harassing their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helen Richard’s survival expectations were already low when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
Yet she had told me that I was done!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for failing to meet their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is absolutely not all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society for Palliative Care at Home in Greater Montreal, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which means falling asleep until the patient dies, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the uneasy patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Patients who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
