With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
The opposite of current currency exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as is often the case with these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the belief that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files from pair to pair.
Approximately 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A small thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to 2 dollars, five months later, before returning today around a dozen dollars (the prices are listed on the site bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to global exchanges in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) was interested in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competitive with the dollar or the euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to progress in a video game that you earn by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But, each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all the nodes in the network are both account holders, verifiers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the manner of an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public ledger, broadcast throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers, and whose winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a phase of file hashing, that is, of transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "crushing" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the imprint.
If, for fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves some margin.
The difficulty of the challenge is also raised with each increase in computational power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in stolen deposits.
"The flaw used does not concern the protocol itself," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also mentions the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Heavyweight actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November, “giant balances” were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which come back cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement with merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
They just need to communicate an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who ensures that it has thousands of users.
There is a general movement of questioning hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to take hold, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in case of success of this currency.
