A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
This is a new poker hit from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally gives it full powers, it has decided to play its va-everything.
Taking everyone on board, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given this Assembly two additional months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text for almost two years, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "betray his word" and "trample the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this use of a hasty vote stems from the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers", these supposedly having to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, the articles were most often voted unanimously.
Commentators were amused by the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, some members of the committee believing that the constituent's pendulum was poorly set.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Article 2 remains the same as the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” the Liberals answer, who see it only as a blow of communication.
For according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
These include Article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, it is worrying because "people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are further intensified by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" tempers Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from the religious vocabulary.
There is reference to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question may arise in the future to what extent civil judges are competent to rule on it.”
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is heavily criticized because of the extensive powers it gives to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the consideration of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will the trials of civilians in military courts be banned, as demanded by human rights associations.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they deem to be a liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences on freedom of expression, in particular from the press.
In addition, no article any longer echoes the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will parade them on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the World Center and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Arguumenty i Fakty has chosen five great reasons to travel to Israel.
Go adore the holy places
It is a must visit: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these "baptismal funds" will be affected by the Divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
It is at this precise place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk along the Rue de la Sufferance or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the anointing and the putting to the tomb.
This is where the Christian center of the world is located, a symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to the Christian legend, the Monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentation, which is the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different denominations leave small words there accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the Masada fortress, an ancient refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain at 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
The old belief is that pagan gods once lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
Impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It mainly exhibits the paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of moldings of visitors and guards of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures of Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Yad Vashem Holocaust Museum or Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children’s memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and enter a total darkness.
Stars are glittering.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned here.
Health and well-being
Israel’s three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, Red Sea and Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the temperature of the water does not fall below 21° while that of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure water contains brine and very easily retains swimmers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
We come to perform a treatment based on salt water, lemon, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it is here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to walk through the narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to take photo shoots from all over Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "conquering" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to euros, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport stop their activities.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scaleless fish and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish pasta, various sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are a lot of well-fed cats that walk around haughty.
We can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These cats love passing places and do not refuse to be entertained.
Renting a car varies by brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Admission to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who has the language, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
As MPs and human rights activists debate what the mandatory language test law will do, fraudsters selling “fake” certificates have already made their appearance in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since December 1, a law has come into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
At the moment, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, private services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the legal foundations.
You will need to validate your language skills in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has the status of official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained certificates or diplomas of education before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the auspices of the Russian Language Institute Pushkin, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions of Russia.
Immigrants will be able to pass the exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce reviews was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But, before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service answer, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, says the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
Protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded cottage where he and dozens of his fellows will be tormented for months without food and without paper and will have to trim between 12 and 14 hours.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they take their passports, and they don't get the expected salary," said Tolib Charipov, head of the Migration Services Directorate for the work of the Tajikistan Migration Service.
Don't argue with me, Mr. Policeman!
However, many citizens of Central Asian republics who want to come to Russia to make money trust that they not only know the language of the country they want to go to, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to make money as soon as the opportunity presents itself.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and weakened."
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will only be for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or Defense to Enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? The administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," Khuchkadamov, a Tajik national, told reporters.
“Do it quickly, don’t lick and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day of the language law's entry into force, it was discovered that migrant registration papers were not the only ones to be fake.
Several false certificates of language examinations have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Fake paper comes out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not take them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: this will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Representatives of the government and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “paper tips”.
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the first-time exam time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against the holders of civilian weapons.
Such is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it is the shootings carried out at weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven.
The police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a permit to carry a weapon by raising it from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma's committee on security and anti-corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the arms law would be introduced to the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "clamping the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, said Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services, while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded in the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that the strengthening of civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from getting supplies to the black market.
According to them, any weapon can be found today in Moscow at a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior maintains that it controls the proliferation of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from the factory to the officer
The black market for arms is supplied through several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who has served ten years at the Ministry of Education and the Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking weapons commands
The first is "military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
“These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians,” Baranets said.
The second type of weapons coming from the black market are those stolen from law enforcement by criminals.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of these have often been subjected to explosions.
"Attested versions indicate that some fires were deliberately set off to cover up the deficit," the former military official said.
For Baranets, weapons manufacturers are there for something.
“We see private weapons factories that do not compete with the competition on the international market and that are flowing weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,” one expert said.
One of the other black market sources is smuggling.
A significant proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former military.
Where do the weapons come from?
The experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from arms portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "by fault of employees whose work is related to weapons," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from “ clandestine digs”.
A seller and consultant at an armoury who asked to remain anonymous assures that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these clandestine excavation specialists; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will look for new goods in military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, for example a TT gun.
We deliver it to him by passing the goods through a wire mesh.
"He transports it to the city and resells it for 900 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> per unit with two chargers," he says.
"It's true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be clarified, they make a purchase of control from the illegal arms dealers," the seller adds.
"Like in a luxury shop "
The seller and the buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I consulted websites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered to come to the Begovaya station where someone was going to take me to a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun, they gave it to me on the spot
Victor Baranets as military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller. I know someone, but I do not trust him.
There are vendors in the markets, but there you also have to come and say, for example, "On behalf of such a person, who asked me to convey that his daughter lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of a person I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give them to him.
Young people are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former militaryman Victor Baranets tried to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
According to him, the patterns have not changed.
We gave him a photo album in which there was "everything we want".
“I thought I was in a luxury store,” recalls the soldier.
There is no secret for the buyer, explains Baranets, we can try everything.
As a potential customer, I don't just buy, we go with the seller into the forest and set up a target.
“They let me shoot and when I’m convinced that the weapon is working well, we start negotiating,” the expert says.
A shop from his couch
