The hands feel nothing.
What are your group’s responses to this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth might very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
At the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to serve as an image support.
It perfectly records the pressures!
But there are also technologies that are really meant to attribute palpability to these "air images": for example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed to a specific point where the finger is located and which gives you the feeling, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of the fingers.
There are also bracelets worn on the wrists that affect the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also a working axis with perspectives.
- And you tried to fool the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he should normally feel when he sees something?
