Birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Space shuttle caravans with Earthlings on board set off in search of a rescue planet.
In order to save humanity, a big question arises: how to continue to make our species live in weightlessness or on a rescue planet?
I don't think there's much choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, even if only by hypothesis.
"It's about Venus and Mars," said Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If on Mars the conditions are more suitable for life, the temperature at the surface of Venus is 500 .
You can only live there at very high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Half a century ago, we were doing experiments on plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from terrestrial varieties.
Then, insects were put into orbit, small drosophilic breeding flies.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how a weightless embryo developed.
At the exit, you get a perfectly normal chicken.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a support, it has to get on its feet and start moving," says Vladimir Sychev, the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP).
When no support was found, the chicks roared disorderly.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die at the end of four days.
"We squinted their eyes twice, then we gave up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," explains Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, the biosatellite " Bion " will only ship species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetus into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural was discovered.
"It was still biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. We have to do this kind of research," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, it is not yet possible to carry out reproductions directly in space.
It's not a big deal.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, humans are capable of this in principle.
The Homo sapiens possesses abstract thought, it is able to create a suitable emotional background.
This type of experience is not carried out for ethical reasons.
Women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the female organism is what humanity has most precious.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would hold after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the theft.
“No one answered that question,” said Vakhtang Vatchnadze, a retired rocket and space engineer.
In June 1964, just one year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Terechkova gave birth to a little girl.
The child’s father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after being twice in orbit and even working in an extra-vehicle environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it poses a danger even during the flights in orbit," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Poliakov.
Yet humanity must seek new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravitation.
Laboratory of Hydrology of the Cosmonaut Preparation Centre: obligatory stage of preparation for flight.
Here, in zero buoyancy, cosmonauts train at extra-vehicle exits.
Water mimics weightlessness.
If for adults, the water is comfortable but yet a foreign environment, for infants, this is their real element.
Small amphibian men seem to confirm this: life on Earth comes from the ocean.
As the baby develops about 9 months in the lymphatic fluid of his mother's belly, it is easier for him to get used to the water afterwards.
This is basically logical, because from his birth to his first bath, it happens only 2 weeks.
“It’s very little to forget,” explains infant swim instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if for the child who has just been born weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravitation, a force of weight.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the abdomen, pelvis atrophy very quickly, the ability to push the baby is lost.
All right, let's ignore that by relying on the birth simulators.
Of course, you can prepare a childbirth in a special room, the woman will manage to get it out.
"And then?" asks Valeriy Poliakov to invite him to reflect on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravitation.
If it does not feel the earthly attraction, the body does not form the skeleton or the muscular system.
One cannot dress an infant like an adult with a special combination for workouts.
It will simply be deprived of its vital needs.
"And this experience that we would consider in this case in imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment will result in the return to Earth of a child with a disability, completely unfit," predicts the Director of the Committee for Bioethics of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
The birth of children in space is still part of the theory.
However, over time this will become a reality when the Earthlings travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the habitat of their space-born offspring.
