Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started working closely with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of ESA projects.
The road from Poland to space, however, started much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles worked on spaceflights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the conference of A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his work "Introduction to Astronautics".
This doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) subsequently became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote numerous books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned propagator of astronautics, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the lunar surface.
As early as 1925, a draisin was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also not clear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the draisin.
The only information known about this draisine is that of the press at the time.
Beginning in 1933, Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the preserved documents that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search was interrupted.
In 1937, the plans for a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda voietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Probl<0xC3><0xA8>me, which contains four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member of it.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
An improved version, RM-1A, was subsequently built, and during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965, was the successor to the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C it was 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites, and in 1978, pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became, after Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The repeal of the Public Utility Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Utility Works Act.
This decision has raised a heated debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to examine this issue from a broader point of view.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
Concretely, this means that the various economic entities and national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (salaries) create a tension on prices.
It is necessary to put under this term the following meaning: a producer strives by importing goods sold at a low price to resist economic competition by "making more expensive" the price of the competitor, with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thus increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, buying cheaply, or disappearing. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social burdens of the State necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect ill-will of the entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole society by this race for profit.
This situation is at such a point of public awareness that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital in different economies lead to a situation in which the governments of different countries are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own populations in order to attract foreign capital to their homes.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account social collapse.
This is manifested mainly in the amendments to the laws in force.
The aim is to economically force its own population to accept the dictation of private capital prices, especially in the field of wages.
This is due, on the one hand, to a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and, on the other, to the restriction of workers' rights in the field of labour legislation.
This results in increasing poverty and deepening disparities between the rich and the poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for years, which cannot meet their needs with their own work.
There are already millions of such people.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay a supplement in order for them to reach the vital minimum.
Such a scandal has been updated, for example, in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of almost all the southern EU Member States undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) or to live with private wages of misery, on the margins of society, in the hands of the poor.
The question here must be asked: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or else a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media say, to get tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, which the directed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital fiercely defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, and even today does not, according to its own selfish interests, direct politics and, by the same, the whole state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is an almost omnipotent lobby in every state.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the drafting of laws to law firms closely linked to the industry.
These bills were then passed in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as Western-type constitutions state, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is evident that liberal-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State was long ago in full turmoil and the functions were attributed by violence.
The bribes, the favors obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The under-the-table and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with absolutely sold votes C" ... ... "Honest people did not seek to get any functions, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls".... ' It really began to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was a failure and autocracy.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
The result is, today as in the past, a decade without precedent for elites, without any effort to carry out profound reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal-type democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future losses of human lives, the humanitarian and social crises we are now witnessing, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Utility Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both at international and internal European level, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the position of private capital monopoly in society for the benefit of the state.
