The movie Argo: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of Islamist students stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was not able to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate aroused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated journeys, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to a rocambole cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to make spots for the filming of a great sci-fi show.
Combination of genres
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan required Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is partly a realistically designed political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful hit, of a betrayal - such as, for example, in the Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
The atmospheres follow each other: documentary-style sequences of Tehran (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been transcribed into the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting ceased to evoke ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The Town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not to take place in his hometown of Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive for its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake film crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject offering in fact few thrilling scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It does very well, it sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always so elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the runway are quite drawn by the hair).
The weakness of Argo lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from that, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it shows itself with moderate interest, enjoying the realization and retro style of the 70s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a history still, in a certain way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the thing.
