The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced, it is enough to contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large nearby company, tells us, "Yes, it's actually beautiful, this building."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
No one wants to go to one of those sleazy libraries anymore, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from Rotterdam’s MVRDV architect’s office, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a curl on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking, puzzled and shouldered, Maas, the confronted, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by activist arguments by one: "Dear common!"
Here it is, my proposal for Spijkenisse’s mountain of books, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain erupted.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a few semi-detached buildings and houses for a total of 50 homes.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is how this dull little town, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of awe-inspiring ugliness, whose white facades invite us to think that they are home to a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Sure, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you as you walk the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant street lights speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls who play ball.
And everywhere books, books, and more books.
"Normally, the library rays are located along the facade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," explains Willy Maas.
We have completely disrupted the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been neatly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes boards, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers don’t want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how we once found ad hoc waste from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
In the Netherlands, one millimeter thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and it saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the mountain top.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to the maintenance of the ideal humidity level of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books lies beneath a glass bell, the sun illuminates the interior only for a short time, even on sunny days.
The thick wooden beams mounted crosswise relative to the glass facade serve as a sunshade, intercepting much of the rays.
The ambience is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "finally found soul".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure helped fill the void in the library that was not yet fully stocked (today it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
Winy Maas once said, “There is nothing worse than a half-empty library.”
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Although she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a difficult political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians' request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
What's wrong?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not too critical of Israel.
In the Libyan uprising of March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is it difficult for Germany to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is revising its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are fighting on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find this role, but are on the path to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term “normal” foreign policy actually mean to the Germans?
It shows a willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, that is, by its exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and its abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has significant opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to hit the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is without a doubt a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine its relations with the United States by opting for abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans understand the German position perfectly.
That is why I believe that the fracture is not so serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respectful of it.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
The United States, on the other hand, announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do the opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
