"Mark Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, she's not sure she'd gain cause.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing’s law firm specializing in property rights violations in the Far East.
Every week, a new file comes to my desk.
Imitators only need a few extra letters to register their trademarks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sporting goods.
Pattloch opens a folder containing the recordings made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company filed the Zegna DF Puma brand, a name that the firm artificially created by taking part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and intellectual property infringement.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell practically only counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are different: his clients charge him with tackling the fact that the Chinese trademark office officially gives Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women are referred to who marry rich men.
Chinese authorities say they have nothing to complain about.
“It’s bad for business, we have to fight this trend,” Pattloch said.
"The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs are in the millions for the sectors concerned, especially in the case of expensive flagship products.
According to the market analysis company CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>15 billion, the third-largest luxury product market in the world and the fastest growing.
However, it is not easy to delete dubious registrations from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch refers to the trials in which the court rejected the complaint, because after a long time, the denomination criticized had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist, as he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought the concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
This is the reason why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, the Volvo buyer, had previously used a blue and white logo that resembled that of BMW. The conflict was settled and Geely had to modify it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost to the plagiarists in Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the famous crocodile’s gaze in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing, however, admits to experiencing some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, last year the office would have moved from a "emergency situation in the work process to a normalized one".
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22 per cent.
Nearly 57,000 cases of this type would have been closed, representing a 75% increase from the previous year.
However, 81,500 procedures are still pending at the office.
Acting is Expensive
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and this means that China is at the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world for the tenth consecutive time.
This would also apply to the total number of legal marks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office would have accounted for 1.8 billion yuan of registration fee.
In other words, each record reported an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg illustrates.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
Of course, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain his Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault, because last names cannot be protected in Germany,” says Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trade mark office therefore rejected the objection of the Munichers.
Freudenberg certainly won the case in the following two instances, but the opposing party continues to fight until today.
Vigilance is required
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "the procedure is long, arduous and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs, and the Archives Service has even had to review the records of the past 100 years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg had even in vain offered the opposing party a “large six-figure euro sum” to settle the dispute.
"That's what it means to us," Wentzler said.
The dangers of the Far East threaten to overwhelm Europe.
This would be the case if imitators from that region ensured the exploitation of unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file the Freudenberg name in Germany for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it was still able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: “Vigilance is at stake.”
Pattloch and he advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trade mark law, foreigners should rather "record also in China everything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs can be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of his legal drama, the company would have to pay license fees to the opposing party for the use of his own name, as Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we would lose our place in the market segment in question.
