However, Egyptians and the world don’t really know what this 61-year-old engineer, who holds a PhD from the American University of Southern California, wants to save.
Will the judiciary be overthrown?
The 234 articles hurriedly drafted by the 100-strong Islamic Constituent Assembly during a fifteen-hour night tour of force are indeed troubling to some extent.
As in previous constitutions, the draft provides that jurisprudence is based on “the principles of Islamic law.”
But what does the word “principles” really mean?
It was and still is a matter of interpretation, and there is good reason to fear that Islamists will use the vague formulation and the resulting legal manoeuvre to apply a stricter interpretation of Sharia.
In any case, it is suggested that a newly introduced article stating that, with regard to all topics related to Sharia, al-Azhar University should be consulted. The institution is the most important Islamic institution in the country and its radiance shines on all Sunni Islamic world.
This may, but does not necessarily mean that the clergy will monitor the legislative apparatus, which would result in the de facto supervision of the judiciary.
Many points of the draft Constitution are subject to interpretation.
Another problematic aspect is the likely maintenance of military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak's reign, these courts tried to repress opponents.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were held by the military.
The state must also, it reads in the draft, protect "the true nature of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morals and values".
From a legal point of view, the wording is so vague that state institutions could even control the content of cinematographic art and literature.
Clearly, it would simply be censorship.
Moreover, no article expressly guarantees equality between men and women.
Instead, another article forbids offending or defaming the Prophet Muhammad or his envoys.
However, the article does not define what an offence is or how it should be punished.
Equally doubtful is the wording suggesting that it is forbidden to "offend people".
Is it enough to draw a cartoon of the president or tell a joke at the expense of a lawman?
Many points are therefore to be interpreted in the draft that Morsi submits to the vote and which, in his own words, will be the subject of a referendum with the Egyptians "very soon".
"The revolution is coming again"
The opposition has been mobilizing for weeks against the digital superiority of Islamists.
On Friday evening, tens of thousands of demonstrators gathered in an unusual concert on Tahrir Square in Cairo, vowing to bring down the sharia before it comes into force.
“The revolution is reborn and we are going to win,” said Hamdin Sabbahi, who came third in the presidential election.
The Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El Baradei said the draft constitution was “thrown into the rubbish bin of history.”
On Twitter, the instant messaging service, he accused Morsi’s supporters of wanting to foment a “putsch against democracy.”
"If he announces the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow it," said Jasser Said, an opposition leader.
"We are not yet tired, the blood of our brothers is not yet atoned for," said Khaled Ali, a politician and member of the opposition.
In addition, several judges have announced that they do not want to monitor the referendum, which would result in its nullity.
"The Qur'an is our Constitution"
For its part, the well-organized Muslim Brotherhood called for a counter-demonstration not on Tahrir Square as a precaution, but on the other side of the Nile, where a great prayer was organized in front of the University of Cairo.
The veiled women and followers of the Salafists, who participated in it in large numbers, chanted: "the people demand the application of the law of God."
“Clean up our country!” they asked Morsi, saying that “the Qur’an [was] their constitution.”
A struggle for sovereignty on the symbolic Tharir Square, where everything began, would soon have engendered a situation similar to that of a civil war.
Obviously, this is what Morsi’s supporters wanted to avoid.
The Muslim Brotherhood said that the opponents of the draft Constitution, as well as its supporters, had expressed themselves loud and clear.
According to them, it is now time to let the people decide by the ballot box the direction that the country should take.
The Islamist project will certainly win the majority.
“Human rights are not mentioned once.”
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry at this imposed constitutional process that should have lasted until February and encompassed all social forces.
This 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) had defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were in prison or in the courts under Mubarak.
He did so not because he shared their conception of the world, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
That's why he was beaten, tried and imprisoned.
"And now, the term is not even pronounced once in the new constitution," he regretted during his interview with Welt am Sonntag.
The extension of Morsi's powers to the three powers discouraged the lawyer.
These measures are blatant violations of the rules of democracy and will lead to a new dictatorship in Egypt.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto strips him of all his powers," Saeda said.
Yet a democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels abandoned, including by the international community, who looks at the battle between different political ideologies on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and nervousness.
It could pay off.
A protester in Tharir Square warns: "You are giving birth to a monster that you will no longer be able to control."
The rakfish of Norway: is it the most fragrant fish in the world?
The five million people who inhabit Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country’s success be linked to the appetite of locals for an extremely fragrant fish?
Take some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty football clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway’s most popular dishes.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this omnipresent smell permeates the air.
The rakfish consists of salt-sprayed trout and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When the darkness settles and it is cold, the Norwegians gather in mass to attend a festival that takes place here, in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
"You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter also known as "Rakfisk General", who is responsible for managing the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
“Some people prefer aquavit to rakfish,” adds Havard.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid getting it under your nose, it’s not bad – it’s reminiscent of a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
The rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in airtight water barrels, then salted in the fall.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish is out and - no doubt with the senses weakened by alcohol - eaten.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, emigrating mainly to the United States.
Now, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, cross the border to come to work.
The rakfisk is considered to be something important, a vital, albeit fragrant, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> each.
Norway does not often talk about it in international news, which is not to her displeasure.
Here, people are not willing to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist extremist who shot 77 people, including women and children.
When they mention this killing, they speak of the “July 22 incident.”
The Norwegians have a hard time accepting that in their peaceful country, one of them could have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 1970s, Norway owes its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
"But oil is not the only reason for our success," explains Anna, our waitress, with blond hair and eyes of a translucent blue, the image of Nordic well-being, with a rakfish tray in hand.
We are - as you say - prudent people.
His English, like that of most people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - everything, except a small percentage of money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries were throwing money through the windows, in the years that led us to the international financial crisis, Norway was able to keep the cords of its stock market tight.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we are happy,” says Anna.
"Without forgetting the rakfisk," she adds in a carefree laugh.
I stand under the snow and queue to buy myself something to eat - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a hamburger made of pulse, a real discovery, it's excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I stay at is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where you can vote for the best of them - or maybe for the smelliest of them.
There's a TV show where the presenter wears a butterfly knot, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score did you give the best fish in the Thor-Juergen Mountains?"
"Here are the points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of aquavit abuse.
Or maybe it's because of the fish emanations.
Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a tough start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, Will Grant, of the BBC, is interested in the difficulties that await him and the expectations of the people, which are numerous.
Road traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic jams are legion in normal time, a security dam has been set up since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
However, the goal was not to prevent people from going to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
