The authorities treated me as if I were an old commere, a proponent of disorder, a crying woman.
They want us to accept what they say and shut up.
“But it’s not normal that there are so many irregularities and omissions,” she said.
When President Pena Nieto receives his scarf on Saturday, it will be accompanied by a heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by crime in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has vowed to make it his priority during his term.
"I hope he will be as good as he was when he was governor," Olvera said in Valle del Bravo, a member of Congress.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, prosecutors said.
Prosecutors are trying to counter the claims of abuse that Bradley Manning allegedly suffered during his detention.
Manning is being held in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to classify the case on the grounds that Manning's kidnapping took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. military history -- has missed many opportunities to complain about the mistreatment he claims to have endured during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints regarding his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defense filed a petition demanding that the Manning case be classified on the grounds that the kidnapping took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified his willingness to commit suicide during his murder.
The military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein discussed with Manning the forms the officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in the Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards had given him was “excellent” and that the treatment he had had inside the prison was overall “very professional.”
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had orally expressed concerns about certain issues and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not report the issues raised.
“They wrote ‘no problem’ (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn’t mean I didn’t raise any problems,” Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the Special Committee that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed indicating a "risk of injury".
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was okay, and I wanted this status to be withdrawn... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Marine Corps military prison base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered suicide when he was in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he had spent the clearest of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had at his disposal were a mattress, blanket, tongs, clothing and his glasses.
He tried to stay in motion, because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also clarified that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so that they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning, during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a cover during the call.
During the judge’s questions on Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard’s order that he should release his cover that could have concealed his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to release her.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic in his slipper or tongs to injure himself, but that he had not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, his pants, and his glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he is found guilty in a court martial, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the least serious crimes and fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors arguing that conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning has been incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include theft of property or public documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information related to national defense.
If all the indictees are detained, he shall be sentenced to life imprisonment.
