Old quarrels, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas is still a failure for peace.
Will there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such hope is in vain.
While the same futile arguments about who started persist, dozens of buildings have been reduced to dust; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza have landed near Tel Aviv, the capital of Israel.
But while the Israelis and Palestinians seem to be stuck in their old conflict, all around them, the Middle East is in full swing.
The Arab Spring has blown everything up, and whether we like it or not, the Palestinians and the Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Perhaps their struggle will intensify even more.
Yet there is every reason to think that this could help them get out of this deadly impasse.
A war that makes no losers or winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to be optimistic.
Although the ceasefire granted on November 21 continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened supporters of the force on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will boast of forcing the Israelis to give up, even if Gaza has wiped out a razor blade.
Having killed some of its leaders and driven the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza into one of the most miserable and overcrowded corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas gains ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of their Fatah rivals, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders might say that time is their ally.
The influence of Islamists in the Arab world is growing stronger, and Hamas has become rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a booming regional power, once Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken the lead for Hamas; as has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf.
Hamas members cheer and say that the growing Islamist bends around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where Hezbollah militia exercises domination, through Syria, where Islamist-oriented rebels can overthrow Bashar El Assad, and up to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten him.
And most importantly, on the southern flank of Israel, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under the presidency of Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and central of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to devote to Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, are cousins of Hamas, and their leaders are more easily reliant on public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as an important actor that can no longer be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, Israel’s hardline supporters will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been put back in a box.
The Iron Dome missile interception system has proven to be effective and many Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will be able to sleep on their two ears – for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America renews its unwavering support; and many European countries have blamed Hamas for being at the root of the latest wave of violence.
But most importantly, Israel prospered, particularly under Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who completely ignored the peace process.
Although rocket fire from Gaza has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared from suicide bombings, notably thanks to the separation barrier that breaches the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and which protects Jewish settlements from continuing to harm themselves.
Mr. Netanyahu, whose Likud party has merged with an even more bellicose party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, has the good part.
Why spoil these Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they were leading the West Bank, would they not launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is best to keep them behind this wall and hit them as soon as they come out of their head.
Perhaps the supporters of the hard line will win; but it may be that the Arab Spring changes the game.
Even if the Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere have little appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address the problems in their own countries.
Israel’s defense budget is more important than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments to settle their economies.
Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to get a ceasefire which is a good thing -- and could mark the beginning of something.
The Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination could create a powder keg that is destined to explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories – a bit like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already weakening democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics are exacerbating this problem as the Arab population grows.
Bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to ring the bell of Hamas will have a diplomatic prize.
Both sides need to be pushed by those from the outside.
The answer remains the one advocated by the reasonable people on each side, and by most of the outside world and by this newspaper: two states, with an assignment of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
One hope, small and short-term, is that the ceasefire will give outsiders the opportunity to defend this cause.
Egypt, which must now strive to end the flow of arms to Gaza, as well as Turkey and Qatar, is better placed than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state in line with the 1967 borders with exchanges of land and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs from outside countries should also put pressure on Hamas and Fatah to unite.
This would contribute far more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming proposal of a pseudo-state to the UN.
Mr. Obama also has every interest in Israel agreeing to negotiate.
During his first term, he did not present his own peace plan.
Back at the White House, he seems equally reluctant to establish one.
It's a very narrow vision.
The stability of the Middle East is a vital issue for America.
This is a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
