Apart from the various photos and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, since Saturday, is the brand name, printed in small letters on all packages.
This is the world’s strictest tobacco packaging regime.
The Australian federal government said the goal was to deter young people from smoking by removing any glamorous representation.
Studies have shown that if people do not start smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they never start.
"Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their brand image," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that revealed, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with a princess.
Although Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has been pushing against this law.
Tobacco manufacturers said it would relaunch black market trade, which would make it easier to access cheaper cigarettes.
“Noxious consequences will result from this legislation,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will sell far more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others said that this law had boosted their activity.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said the demand for cigarette cases, including silicone to hide the horrific packaging, has risen sharply two months ago since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco contested the law and lost in Australia's high court.
Ha said Zico has sold 6,000 of them to wholesalers and is awaiting stock renewal.
For us, business is good.
The only nuisance, experts say, is the popularity of social media and the segment of the population targeted by the plan.
After a series of Australian laws banning TV advertising, sports sponsorship and the obligation for retailers to hide cigarettes, tobacco marketing is now available online.
Australia has banned web advertising by local businesses and sites, but it cannot prevent foreign sites from doing so.
"If you work in tobacco marketing and you only have a small showcase to promote your products, the Internet is the place to go," said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in contributions from some lambda citizens in favor of brands on social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
We have to ask ourselves if this is a simple citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes and who has made the effort to make a video, or if this is a marketing campaign orchestrated by an agency?
British American Tobacco Australia said the industry is focusing on the new regulation in force rather than marketing.
The industry has gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to contest these new court decisions - these countries have told the WHO that trade is unfairly disadvantaged, although none of these countries have had significant trade with Australia.
A decision by the WTO is expected to be taken in the course of 2013.
Plibersek said the government had held discussions with other countries regarding similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to make packaging warning photos mandatory in 2001.
Now, these warnings are present in 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
More stringent laws are currently under study in England, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia remain insensitive to these photos.
The pictures don't bother me.
I ignore them.
"You take a cigarette and you store the package," Victor El Hage said when buying a package with a picture of a tumour in his mouth.
To be honest, the only reason I'm gonna get arrested is my little girl.
