In a constantly connected world, it can be good to get bored.
I spent five hours at an airport during the Thanksgiving period because our plane had mechanical problems and we had to wait for the arrival of another plane.
Therefore, I have had enough time to reflect on the theme of boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight is pretty boring, even when you have books, magazines and iPhones to distract you (not to mention duty-free shops).
But more and more, some academics and experts specialized in the development of the child are praising boredom.
It is perfectly normal for us - and our children - to get bored from time to time, they say.
This forces the brain to take interesting paths, and even to nurture creativity.
And as we are, for the most part, constantly facing several types of screens, we no longer know the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome the annoyance with open arms?
Oh, yeah.
And no.
But I'll be back.
First of all, like many people, I thought boredom was a rather recent phenomenon, especially since we have more free time.
But this is not the case, says Peter Toohey, professor of Greco-Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011).
"The boredom goes back a long way," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are Latin graffiti that evoke boredom, they go back to the first century.
Then there is the definition that we give to boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined, and debated, in different ways, said John D. Eastwood, associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After going through many publications and submitting the idea to a discussion group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience of “wanting to do something, but not getting started in a satisfying activity.”
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task even though he would like it.
With apathy, he says, there is no desire to do anything.
What is at the heart of the boredom, he said, is "the interruption of the attention process, associated with a mean mood and the feeling that time passes slowly."
Boredom can strongly resemble depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that if the two can be related, people who get bored tend to think the problem comes from the environment or the world, while depressed people think the problem comes from them.
Sometimes we think we get bored when it is actually a problem of concentration.
As part of their study, "The Uningaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," which was published in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and colleagues highlighted an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a person's voice on tape, a magazine article.
Some groups heard, from the room next door, too loud a sound of a TV show that had no connection, others just heard the TV show, and the third group did not hear the soundtrack at all.
Those who heard TV at a low sound level said they were more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, but didn't know why, and attributed this concentration problem to boredom.
When you’re trying to focus on a difficult or demanding task, a distraction can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, when you perform a boring task, "like looking at objects on a string, music can help you not get bored."
In fact, he says, now we know that when we twist or scratch, these gestures, often seen as signs of boredom, are actually a good way to stay physically more alert.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to giggle learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to remain motionless,” said Professor Fenske.
We all get bored one day or another - the delay of my flight, a speaker with a monochord voice, a particularly boring film.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To measure this, researchers developed a “boredom predisposition scale” in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements such as, “Among the tasks I perform, many of them are repetitive and monotonous,” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have time to do everything.”
Using such a scale, researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a psychology professor at the University of West Florida, and in particular need numerous and varied stimulations.
But in general, teenagers are quickly blasphemed.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of individual and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment during which he contacted nearly 400 teens and their parents seven to eight times a day via a beeper.
He noted that 32 percent of teens reported getting bored at school and during their homework, while 23 percent reported getting bored when they were not at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether today’s boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he added that he knew that “teenager is a period when boredom reaches its highest level,” particularly because children and adolescents don’t have much control over what they want to do.
If I ask my question: is boredom good for you?
Sometimes not, because in its extreme form, it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, make bets or abuse certain substances to pass the time, as studies show.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers evoke a link between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying the problem for more than two decades.
“Annoyance is the way the brain has found to let you know that you should do something else,” said Gary Marcus, a psychology professor at N.Y.U.
But the brain doesn’t always know what is the most appropriate thing to do.
If you get bored and use that energy to play the guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
But if you watch TV, it will make you happy in the short term, but not in the long term.
So if your child gets bored and you give him an iPad, he will not get bored anymore, but he will not have learned to take care of himself or to self-regulate, says Professor Fenske.
And "this self-regulation goes from one situation to another," he says.
Your child not only learns to have fun, he gets more control of himself in other areas.
I don't think we should glorify boredom.
Just as I don't think we should criticize it either.
Feeling comfortable outside of the constant bubbling that activities and technology generate is the goal we should be striving for.
Professor Eastwood agrees on this point.
“We need to get bored more often, but boredom awakens an acute and frenetic desire to be connected to something that makes sense,” he said.
According to him, what people are looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy downtime.
"In an environment where we're constantly overstimulated," he added, "it's hard to find ways to jump into something when the noise stops."
