The World's Toughest Job: Kawah Ijen's Human Mules
For four euros, the Indonesian volcano’s carriers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make their living carrying the sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He has to work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfur gas from the earth's intestines solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large rocks of sulfur, which weigh a total of almost 70 kilograms, he installs them in two baskets of bamboo that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that culminates at 2,386 meters of altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb that distance, in a tortoise-like fashion, keeping their balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the cliff.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once up, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and bearing the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company has installed a little below at 1,850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) per kilogram of sulfur.
