A U.S. court-appointed judgment on appeal ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group’s debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, setting a precedent that is detrimental to all domestic companies with branches in the neighboring country and with solvency problems.
Thus, it seems that the survival procedures of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the star-studded country, in contravention of international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgment handed down on June 15 by Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenseless against the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s leading glass manufacturer to sue the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge in the case points out that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, states that the main proceeding is the formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law had been created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Second, the judgment establishes that without the inter-company voting, recognized in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts contracted by subsidiaries of Vitro to the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
