The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Mexican government on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the Court") detailing Vitro's procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, noting that it freed him from the conventions signed by the two countries to bring it to the same level as paragraph 15 of the bankruptcy law.
In addition, he noted that the country had adhered to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules for cross-border insolvency cases, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
