Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
Basketball wrestler "Hetin" Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as great as that of Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a cerebral hemorrhage sentenced him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, national basketball team player, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN president, with both the Cowboys of Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n and the Cowboys.
"I've worn several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalls during a visit to Primera Hora at his home in Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n, where he lives with his fiancée Isabel, his 50th wife.
“Basketball has been my life.
Reyes doesn't exaggerate when he makes that claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and souvenirs that remind his itinerary out of standards, testify to this.
Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loves most are those that remind him of his time as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
"It was my best years, the ones I took the most advantage of because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships starting in 1967, whether as a manager, co-manager or manager.
This makes many years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired at the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was the leader here at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), who told me, "I have a tough player for you, he's two meters tall.
