The Death of Actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide for the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played a unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved most," the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and later, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, her press attaché, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
“He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the fullest,” Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed liver cirrhosis to Larry Hagman in 1992 and he had admitted to drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television as an ordinary guy in the series "Jinny of My Dreams" broadcast on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film roles include critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the deliciously detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman was most successful.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their loved ones aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Killed J.R.?", invented to entertain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, has generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in betting.
Thanks to this, among others, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screens and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had made her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest businessman and an infidel husband who was trying to imprison his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
“I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R.,” Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "Here's the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as a "huge man, both on the small screen and in life."
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the heart of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" aired a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already finished for the second season and a sixth is underway, the channel reported.
At the moment, neither Warner nor TNT have communicated on how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
Originally from Fort Worth, Texas, he is the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who gained fame with classic works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Mary Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to her in 1931 when she was married to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He took his first steps on the New York theatre scene in the early 1950s and served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
It was there that he met the young Swedish interior decorator Maj Axelsson and he married him.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for many years in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoirs "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
“I didn’t write anything in this book that could hurt anyone or affect them in any way,” he told reporters at the time.
After his liver transplant, he became an active organ donation activist and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist concerned patients.
"I advise them, I give them back confidence, I come with them when they come for surgery and after," he said in 1996.
I try to offer them a little comfort, like, "Don't be afraid, it won't be easy for a while, but it's going to be okay."
He has also been an anti-tobacco activist and has participated in several campaigns.
A course on the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a lecture on the end of the world, he knew that he was throwing an irresistible hook there: the end of the "great reckoning" of the Mayan calendar, on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal gulf that some have dubbed "the Armageddon of Debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists thought it would trigger.
“I didn’t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I’ve ever known,” Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we recount it, it was a very good period.
And it must be remembered that what is bad is good for those who believe in the Apocalypse.
And he's not the only professor to give lectures on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We are analyzing this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared to real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled "The End of the World".
"We are adding '2012' to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world doesn't disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
“It was complete in two hours,” said Restall about his high-level student course, which was comprised of 35 students.
We received emails several weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic movies.
“I had never heard of a course that taught this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone one professor, told us to believe in the end-of-the-world date of December 21.
“Our first project dealt with Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,” says Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old senior student at Temple, who is from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is an apocalypse-related anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, that causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a surge in these speculations.
“In other parts of the world, people don’t think about it,” he says.
This is mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew there were classes on "the end of the world".
“The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world,” he said, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, we have talked about the many supposed dates of the Last Judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a 7-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many told us that they thought they were going to "end of the world" parties.
"Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
